t application of Enlightenment reasoning to English legal history. Loving Justice contends that Blackstone's work extends beyond making sense of English law to invoke emotions such as desire, disgust, sadness, embarrassment, terror, tenderness, and happiness. By enlisting an affective aesthetics to represent English law as just, Blackstone created an evocative poetics of justice whose influence persists across the Western world. In doing so, he encouraged readers to feel as much as reason their way to justice. Ultimately, Temple argues that the Commentaries offers a complex map of our affective relationship to juridical culture, one that illuminates both individual and communal understandings of our search for justice, and is crucial for understanding both justice and injustice today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEmotions in literature. 0aJustice in literature. 0aLaw and aesthetics. 0aLawxPsychological aspects. 0aLawzEnglandxHistory. 0aPractice of lawzEnglandxPsychological aspects. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aCommentaries on the Laws of England.  aEnglish legal history.  aGuantanamo Bay.  aHarper Lee.  aLaw and Humanities.  aNathaniel Hawes.  aOnslow v. Horne.  aTerry Lee Morris.  aWestminster Hall.  aWollstonecraft.  aaesthetics.  aaffective aesthetics.  abodies.  aclose reading.  acommodification.  acruel optimism.  acuratorial reading.  aelectric shock.  aempathy.  aempire.  aexcessive subjectivity.  agothic.  agradualism.  agraveyard poets.  aharmonic justice.  ahistory of emotions.  ajury trial.  amarriage law.  aorientalism.  apeine forte et dure.  apoetics.  apoetry.  aproductive melancholia.  areal